            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was thirteen when his father, smelling of sawdust from a weekend project, spread the deed to their San Jose house on the kitchen table. \"This,\" his father said, tapping the paper, \"is real. This is security, Ramin.\" The weight of that document, the finality of their name on it, felt more significant than any A+ on a report card. It was the first time he truly understood what being *Kheradmand*\u2014being wise\u2014was meant to build: something solid you could stand on, forever.\n\n2.\nNew York, September 2008. The air in the office was thick with a silence that screamed louder than the trading floor ever had. He remembers watching a Managing Director, a man he'd once revered, quietly placing a framed photo of his family into a cardboard box. The numbers on the screen had become ghosts, devouring fortunes overnight. At that moment, Ramin felt a visceral need for something he could touch\u2014brick, steel, land. The abstract world had failed; he needed to get back to the real one.\n\n3.\nHe can still picture Sarah\u2019s face, not angry but resigned, when he called to cancel their Sonoma trip. \"The Tokyo deal is closing,\" he\u2019d explained, the words feeling hollow even to him. He was standing on his balcony, a titan of finance sacrificing a weekend of wine tasting. The silence on the other end of the line was the sound of a future being erased. He won the deal, but that night, alone in his apartment, he keenly felt the loss of something no contract could ever recapture.\n\n4.\nIt was the acquisition of a brick-and-timber building in SoMa, around his 38th birthday. The culmination of months of modeling and negotiation. After signing the final papers, he stood across the street, looking at its facade. He didn\u2019t see history or beauty; he saw IRR projections, seismic retrofit costs, and potential rent-roll increases. The victory felt clean, precise, and utterly hollow. He had conquered another piece of the city, yet felt no more a part of it than before.\n\n5.\nJust last winter, walking home, the sound of the organ spilled from the doors of Grace Cathedral, warm and complex against the cold night air. He paused, watching a couple laugh as they exited, their hands intertwined. In that moment, the perfect geometry of his Nob Hill life felt profoundly empty. The security he had built, brick by financial brick, felt like a beautiful, silent vault. He wondered what kind of wisdom it took to build a life filled with that kind of music."
